]
```
Here is an example of how you might implement this endpoint in a server-side language like Node.js using the Express.js framework:
```
const express = require('express');
const app = express();

const items = [
  { id: 1, name: 'Item 1', description: 'This is the first item' },
  { id: 2, name: 'Item 2', description: 'This is the second item' },
  { id: 3, name: 'Item 3', description: 'This is the third item' }
];

app.get('/api/items', (req, res) => {
  res.json(items);
});

app.listen(3000, () => {
  console.log('Server started on port 3000');
});
```
This code sets up an Express.js server that listens for GET requests to the `/api/items` endpoint. When a request is received, it returns the `items` array in JSON format using the `res.json()` method.

You can test this endpoint by sending a GET request to `http://localhost:3000/api/items` in your web browser or using a tool like `curl` from the command line:
```
curl http://localhost:3000/api/items
```
This should return the JSON response shown above.

